<paragraph blockId="27.[151,593,2005,2031]" box="[151,593,2005,2031]" pageId="27" pageNumber="68">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,593,2005,2031]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="27" pageNumber="68" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius, 1775" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[151,593,2005,2031]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruderatus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,593,2005,2031]" pageId="27" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,374,2005,2031]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="68">Bombus ruderatus</emphasis>
(Fabricius, 1775)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,151,824]" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">
It is a long-tongued bumblebee species, western Palearctic, introduced in 
<collectingCountry box="[993,1145,151,176]" name="New Zealand" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1203,1267,151,176]" name="Chile" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">Chile</collectingCountry>
, from where it has spread to 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmid-Hempel et al. 2014" authorityName="Schmid-Hempel et al." authorityYear="2014" box="[321,795,188,213]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Argentina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<collectingCountry box="[321,433,188,213]" name="Argentina" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(Schmid-Hempel 
<emphasis box="[651,713,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">et al.</emphasis>
2014)
</taxonomicName>
. According to Rasmont 
<emphasis box="[1089,1151,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">et al.</emphasis>
(2015), the species has disappeared from most of its historic locations in the west- and central European lowlands, but despite this regional regression, is considered as Least Concern in the 
<collectionCode box="[704,772,260,284]" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">IUCN</collectionCode>
Red List of European Bees.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="69" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,151,824]" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">
It has also been found on 
<collectingRegion box="[484,577,295,320]" country="Portugal" name="Madeira" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">Madeira</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[630,712,296,320]" country="Portugal" name="Acores" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">Azores</collectingRegion>
, northern Africa and in the Iberian Peninsula, where it used to be very abundant, between 350 and 2200 meters of altitude (mostly below 1650 meters, but reaching 2800 meters of altitude in Sierra Nevada, 
<collectingCountry box="[442,507,367,392]" name="Spain" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">Spain</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Castro" box="[529,669,368,392]" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" refString="Castro, L. (1993) Sobre los Bombinae (Hymenoptera, Apidae) de la Sierra de Albarracin (I). Zapateri Revista aragonesa de Entomologia, 3, 5 - 14." type="journal article" year="1993">Castro 1993</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ornosa" box="[680,1021,367,392]" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" refString="Ornosa, C. &amp; Ortiz-Sanchez, F. J. (2004) Hymenoptera: Apoidea I. In: Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cientificas (Ed.), Fauna Iberica. Fol. 23. Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales, CSIC, Madrid, pp. 1 - 556." type="book chapter" year="2004">Ornosa &amp; Ortiz-Sánchez 2004</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Vargas" box="[1032,1237,367,392]" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" refString="Vargas, P., Ornosa, C., Blanco, J. L., Romero, D., Fernandez-Mazuecos, M. &amp; Rodriguez-Girones, M. A. (2013) En busqueda de areas de diversidad genetica en Sierra Nevada. In: Ramirez, L. &amp; Asensio, B. (Eds.), Proyectos de investigacion en parques nacionales. MAGRAMA, Madrid, 223 - 242." type="book chapter" year="2013">
Vargas 
<emphasis box="[1114,1170,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
). It shows a slight preference for open areas in the Iberian Peninsula, but it has also been collected in forests, foraging on species of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,258,439,464]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Apiaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[270,396,440,464]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[408,563,439,464]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Boraginaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[575,682,439,464]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[695,801,439,464]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Liliaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[812,917,439,464]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Oleaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Oleaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[930,1085,440,463]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Papaveraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Papaveraceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1098,1207,440,463]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1218,1388,439,464]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ranunculaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Ranunculaceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,344,476,501]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Scrophulariaceae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Castro" box="[358,499,476,500]" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" refString="Castro, L. (1993) Sobre los Bombinae (Hymenoptera, Apidae) de la Sierra de Albarracin (I). Zapateri Revista aragonesa de Entomologia, 3, 5 - 14." type="journal article" year="1993">Castro 1993</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ornosa" box="[510,855,476,501]" pageId="28" pageNumber="69" refString="Ornosa, C. &amp; Ortiz-Sanchez, F. J. (2004) Hymenoptera: Apoidea I. In: Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cientificas (Ed.), Fauna Iberica. Fol. 23. Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales, CSIC, Madrid, pp. 1 - 556." type="book chapter" year="2004">Ornosa &amp; Ortiz-Sánchez 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,151,824]" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">
In southern 
<collectingCountry box="[344,408,511,536]" name="Spain" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">Spain</collectingCountry>
(ssp. 
<emphasis box="[484,592,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="69">rondensis</emphasis>
Castro 1991) it was assessed as Near Threatened in the Red Book of Andalusian Invertebrates (Ornosa &amp; Ortiz-Sánchez 2008).
</paragraph>
